  EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Audit Target: Post-3D identity milestone codebase
Prior Audit:  audits/audit-2026-04-11T21-22-10.log (Landing v1 Readiness)

This audit focuses on refactoring opportunities, simplification, and
architectural improvements that emerged from implementing the 3D identity
system (Infinity geometry, GradientMaterial shader, ParticleTrail, hooks).

Overall System Health: GOOD (8/10)

The 3D identity system is architecturally clean and well-modularized.
The geometry / material / effects separation is sound and swap-ready.
The main gaps are dead code artifacts left from the pre-milestone state
and a critical functional gap in the Infinity interaction model.

Findings by severity:
  HIGH   ─  2
  MEDIUM ─  7
  LOW    ─  8

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  1. ARCHITECTURE & STRUCTURE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 8/10

Strengths:
  ✓ Clean three-layer separation in features/three/:
      geometry/   → pure parametric shape definitions
      materials/  → PBR and shader-augmented surface materials
      effects/    → post-processing and particle systems
  ✓ Dedicated hooks/  folder with useInfinityInteraction and useInfinityMotion.
  ✓ Infinity component is fully swap-aware — GeometryComponent and
    MaterialComponent are injected as props, enabling hot-swapping without
    touching the frame loop or interaction layer.
  ✓ LandingVisualLayer is isolated from LandingBackground — the 3D canvas
    can evolve independently of the cosmic starfield and scroll logic.
  ✓ Scene.tsx cleanly separates lighting setup from object composition.
  ✓ All public boundaries have index.ts barrel exports.

Findings:

  [HIGH] R-ARCH-01: TorusKnot is deprecated legacy code still in the public API.
    File: src/features/three/TorusKnot/TorusKnot.tsx
    Export: src/features/three/index.ts → `export { TorusKnot }`
    Export: src/features/three/geometry/index.ts → `export { TorusKnotGeometry }`
    The TorusKnot component was the first-generation 3D identity object. It has
    been superseded by the Infinity + InfinityGeometry + GradientMaterial system.
    TorusKnot.tsx is 244 lines of inline interaction logic (hold timer, inertia,
    velocity, touch-scroll prevention) that duplicates code now properly
    abstracted into useInfinityInteraction.
    Risk: import confusion, maintenance burden, bundle bloat.
    Action: Remove TorusKnot.tsx, TorusKnotGeometry.tsx (the geometry component
    wrapping `<torusKnotGeometry>`), and their barrel exports. Keep the
    useInfinityInteraction hook — it is the canonical abstraction.
    Note: TorusKnotGeometry (the extracted component) adds no value over the
    native `<torusKnotGeometry>` JSX element; it was a stepping-stone component
    and can be removed with it.

  [MED] R-ARCH-02: useInfinityMotion hook is dead code — never imported.
    File: src/features/three/hooks/useInfinityMotion/useInfinityMotion.ts
    The hook provides rotation accumulation, velocity tracking, inertia, and
    idle motion. It was extracted to separate motion concerns but the Infinity
    component intentionally omits rotation (it is the "Stable Edition").
    The hook is fully implemented but has zero consumers.
    Risk: maintenance confusion — developers may wonder if it should be used.
    Action (Option A): Delete the hook if the "stable, no-rotation" policy is
      permanent. Document the design decision in Infinity.tsx header.
    Action (Option B): Reintroduce to Infinity.tsx when idle rotation is
      desired (e.g., subtle slow drift). This is the preferred path if the
      identity element benefits from gentle motion.
    Recommendation: Option B — reconnect the hook behind a `effects.rotation`
      flag in InfinityProps, defaulting to false to preserve the current
      stable behavior.

  [LOW] R-ARCH-03: InfinityProps.children is declared but never consumed.
    File: src/features/three/Infinity/Infinity.types.ts
    InfinityProps includes `children?: ReactNode` but the Infinity component
    never renders {children}. The field was likely added speculatively.
    Action: Remove the `children` prop from InfinityProps and the ReactNode
    import from Infinity.tsx unless a use case is identified.

  [LOW] R-ARCH-04: hooks/ folder has no barrel export.
    Files: src/features/three/hooks/useInfinityInteraction/index.ts
           src/features/three/hooks/useInfinityMotion/index.ts
    There is no src/features/three/hooks/index.ts aggregating both hooks.
    The three/index.ts barrel does not re-export the hooks at all.
    Action: Add src/features/three/hooks/index.ts and expose hooks through
    the top-level features/three/index.ts barrel so consumers can import
    from "@portfolio/features/three" consistently.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  2. CODE QUALITY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 7/10

Strengths:
  ✓ TypeScript strict mode throughout; no `any` types observed.
  ✓ GradientMaterial cleanly separates GLSL generation into buildGradientFragmentShader
    — the shader builder is independently testable and not tangled in React.
  ✓ INFINITY_PATH pre-computation at module level correctly avoids per-frame
    re-computation and sidesteps React hooks immutability rules.
  ✓ Consistent use of useRef for frame-mutation state to avoid re-renders.
  ✓ useFadeUp hook cleanly encapsulates reduced-motion branching.
  ✓ Section component cleanly abstracts repeated page-section layout.

Findings:

  [HIGH] R-QUAL-01: Infinity component has no window-level drag handlers —
    the "engaged" state is a functional dead end.
    File: src/features/three/Infinity/Infinity.tsx
    File: src/features/three/hooks/useInfinityInteraction/useInfinityInteraction.ts
    The useInfinityInteraction hook correctly manages three-state machine
    (idle → pending → engaged) and returns Three.js mesh event handlers
    (handlePointerDown, handlePointerEnter, handlePointerLeave).
    However: once the interaction enters "engaged" state (after 250ms hold),
    there are no window-level listeners to track pointer movement or release.
    The Infinity.tsx component does not register pointermove, pointerup, or
    touchmove handlers anywhere. This means:
      - The cursor changes to "grabbing" but dragging does nothing.
      - Releasing the pointer never triggers releaseEngaged().
      - The component is stuck in "engaged" state until the canvas unmounts.
    Compare with the deprecated TorusKnot.tsx which registers all three
    window-level handlers in a useEffect, correctly covering the full
    pointer lifecycle.
    Action: Move window-level handlers into useInfinityInteraction as a
    useEffect (paired with the existing useInfinityMotion hook), or add a
    separate useEffect in Infinity.tsx that calls releaseEngaged on pointerup
    and cancelHold on pointermove that exceeds SCROLL_CANCEL_PX.
    This is the most critical functional gap in the current 3D system.

  [MED] R-QUAL-02: InteractionState type is duplicated across two modules.
    Definitions:
      src/features/three/hooks/useInfinityInteraction/useInfinityInteraction.ts
        → `export type InteractionState = "idle" | "pending" | "engaged";`
      src/lib/debug/debugStore.ts
        → `export type InteractionState = "idle" | "pending" | "engaged";`
    These are distinct type declarations for the same concept. If the states
    evolve in one place, the other can drift silently.
    Action: Export InteractionState only from useInfinityInteraction and
    import it in debugStore.ts:
      `import type { InteractionState } from "@portfolio/features/three/hooks/useInfinityInteraction";`

  [MED] R-QUAL-03: debugStore has rotation/velocity fields that are never updated.
    File: src/lib/debug/debugStore.ts
    DebugInteractionData includes rotX, rotY, velX, velY fields but
    Infinity.tsx only calls setDebugInteraction({ interactionState, isHovered }).
    The rotation fields are never populated because Infinity is the "Stable
    Edition" without rotation. They are initialized to 0 and stay 0 forever.
    Action: Remove rotX, rotY, velX, velY from DebugInteractionData (and
    the _interaction initializer) until rotation is reintroduced. This keeps
    the debug panel's data model honest.

  [MED] R-QUAL-04: InfinityGeometry has a dead depthScale variable.
    File: src/features/three/geometry/InfinityGeometry/InfinityGeometry.tsx
    In InfinityCurve.getPoint():
      const z = 0;              // always zero — lemniscate is 2D
      const depthScale = 0.2;   // comment says "VERY slight depth"
    The final return is `new THREE.Vector3(x * horizontalScale, y * verticalScale,
    z * depthScale)` which computes `0 * 0.2 = 0`. The z axis is always zero.
    depthScale is a dead constant — it multiplies a zero operand.
    The comment "VERY slight depth" is misleading since no depth is applied.
    Action: Remove the depthScale constant. Either:
      (A) Keep z = 0 and document "lemniscate is planar", or
      (B) Introduce a real depth wobble using a different curve variable
          (e.g., `z = sin(angle) * depthScale`) if spatial depth is desired.

  [MED] R-QUAL-05: Three content sections share an identical template structure.
    Files: MusicSection.tsx, DevelopmentSection.tsx, PublishingSection.tsx
    All three sections follow the same structure:
      - module-level `visual` constant with placeholder Lottie animation
      - async server component calling getTranslations
      - Section wrapper with identical child pattern (p.description, p.placeholder, Link)
    The only differences are the i18n namespace and the `id`/`aria-label` values.
    This creates a high-maintenance pattern — any structural change requires
    updating three files.
    Action: Extract a shared SectionTemplate or data-driven approach using a
    `sections` configuration array. Each entry would define:
      { id, namespaceKey, href, background }
    The three components can then be generated from a single template or merged
    into one `LandingSections` component.
    Note: Keep as separate components if sections are expected to diverge
    significantly in structure. Flag for review when real content is added.

  [LOW] R-QUAL-06: GradientMaterial ref resolution uses a type assertion.
    File: src/features/three/materials/GradientMaterial/GradientMaterial.tsx
    The `resolvedMatRef` fallback:
      `(matRef as React.MutableRefObject<MeshStandardMaterial | null>) ?? localMatRef`
    uses a type assertion to cast the incoming `React.Ref<MeshStandardMaterial>`
    to a mutable ref. This is necessary because React.Ref can be a callback ref
    or null, not just a RefObject. However, the cast is unsafe — a callback ref
    would silently break the ref-reading code in useEffect.
    Action: Accept `React.RefObject<MeshStandardMaterial | null>` (not
    `React.Ref`) in MaterialProps, or use `useImperativeHandle` / a separate
    callback to safely pass the resolved ref back to callers.

  [LOW] R-QUAL-07: LandingEntry STORAGE_KEY is not co-located with theme key.
    File: src/features/landing/LandingEntry/LandingEntry.tsx
    `const STORAGE_KEY = "landing-entered"` is a module-local constant.
    The theme key (`THEME_STORAGE_KEY`) lives in lib/theme.tsx and is exported.
    All session storage keys should be centralized (e.g., in config/ or a
    lib/storageKeys.ts) so key conflicts and typos are caught in one place.
    Action: Export LANDING_ENTRY_KEY from a shared constants location and
    import it in LandingEntry.tsx.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  3. PERFORMANCE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 8/10

Strengths:
  ✓ Scene.tsx loaded via next/dynamic with ssr: false — no SSR hydration risk.
  ✓ INFINITY_PATH is a module-level Float32Array computed once at load time,
    not inside a component or hook — optimal for the 80-particle loop.
  ✓ Particles driven imperatively via posAttrRef.needsUpdate — no React
    re-renders from the particle animation loop.
  ✓ Emissive glow interpolated each frame with lerp — smooth without
    triggering React state updates.
  ✓ CosmicBackground uses CSS radial-gradient + backgroundSize for the
    starfield — far more efficient than canvas or SVG particle systems.
  ✓ GradientMaterial shader runs on GPU via Three.js onBeforeCompile hook —
    no CPU-side color computation per frame.

Findings:

  [MED] R-PERF-01: CosmicBackground tracks both global scrollY and element
    scrollYProgress simultaneously, regardless of active mode.
    File: src/components/ui/CosmicBackground/CosmicBackground.tsx
    In hero mode, useScroll({ target: containerRef }) is called and attaches
    a ResizeObserver + scroll listener to the containerRef element even though
    only the global scrollY is needed. The same pattern exists in
    useScrollParallax (noted in prior audit).
    Impact: two unnecessary scroll subscriptions per CosmicBackground instance.
    Action: Split into two separate effects / hooks gated by the `mode` prop,
    or pass a stable `undefined` ref only in global mode to short-circuit
    Framer Motion's element-level tracking.

  [LOW] R-PERF-02: ParticleTrail iterates over all 80 particles every frame
    without reduced-motion awareness.
    File: src/features/three/effects/ParticleTrail/ParticleTrail.tsx
    The trail runs at full speed regardless of the user's
    prefers-reduced-motion preference. It does not check the media query.
    Action: Read useReducedMotion() or check the media query on mount; if
    reduced motion is preferred, either hide the particles entirely or set
    speed = 0 so particles are stationary (preserving the visual texture
    without animation).

  [LOW] R-PERF-03: BloomEffect renders an EffectComposer unconditionally.
    File: src/features/three/effects/BloomEffect/BloomEffect.tsx
    The EffectComposer adds a post-processing pass on every frame. On low-end
    or power-constrained devices, this is a meaningful overhead.
    Action: Consider adding a `enabled` prop that conditionally renders the
    composer, or gate it behind the reducedMotion check since bloom is a
    purely decorative effect.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  4. VISUAL SYSTEM
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 7/10

Strengths:
  ✓ GradientMaterial creates a premium flowing color shift (indigo → purple →
    cyan) driven by a GPU-side shader — visually distinguishable from a
    simple PBR material.
  ✓ Three-point + rim lighting in Scene.tsx produces intentional depth and
    edge separation. Light values adapt correctly to light/dark theme.
  ✓ ParticleTrail uses AdditiveBlending — particles accumulate brightness at
    overlap points, reinforcing the Bloom glow organically.
  ✓ Viewport-aware scaling in Infinity.tsx ensures the lemniscate renders
    correctly on portrait mobile without clipping.
  ✓ CosmicBackground star field adapts color and opacity correctly to both
    light and dark themes.
  ✓ ThemeToggle now cycles through all three modes (dark / light / system)
    rather than being a simple boolean toggle.

Findings:

  [MED] R-VIS-01: ThemeToggle uses emoji glyphs for icons.
    File: src/components/ui/ThemeToggle/ThemeToggle.tsx
    Icons: { light: "☀️", dark: "🌙", system: "🖥" }
    Emoji rendering is inconsistent across operating systems, browsers, and
    screen readers. Some emoji may not render at the expected size or color.
    The codebase already installs lucide-react (which includes Sun, Moon, and
    Monitor icons) via the Icon component at src/components/ui/Icon/.
    Action: Replace emoji with lucide-react icons using the existing
    `<Icon>` wrapper. Example:
      light → <Icon icon={Sun} size={16} />
      dark  → <Icon icon={Moon} size={16} />
      system → <Icon icon={Monitor} size={16} />

  [MED] R-VIS-02: IdentityBlock renders a Lottie placeholder that is now
    visually redundant with the 3D canvas behind it.
    File: src/features/landing/IdentityBlock/IdentityBlock.tsx
    The placeholder.json Lottie animation in IdentityBlock floats above the
    full-viewport Infinity 3D canvas. Both are identity visual elements
    competing for attention at the center of the screen.
    Action: Either:
      (A) Replace with a text-based or SVG monogram/avatar that is
          compositionally distinct from the 3D object behind it, or
      (B) Remove the Lottie element from IdentityBlock entirely, letting
          the 3D canvas serve as the sole visual identity anchor.
    The 3D canvas already renders through the IdentityBlock container
    (pointer-events layering is correct). The placeholder Lottie adds
    visual noise rather than brand value.

  [LOW] R-VIS-03: Infinity hover scale target (1.04×) and TorusKnot hover
    scale (1.05×) diverge slightly — minor consistency issue.
    File: src/features/three/Infinity/Infinity.tsx (targetNorm: 1.04)
    File: src/features/three/TorusKnot/TorusKnot.tsx (targetScale: 1.05)
    If TorusKnot is removed per R-ARCH-01, this becomes irrelevant.
    Otherwise, standardize on a single hover multiplier via a shared constant.

