Findings:

  [LOW] R-DX-01: No Storybook stories for the 3D feature system.
    The 3D components (Infinity, Scene, effects, materials) have no Storybook
    stories. This makes it difficult to develop or review visual changes to
    the 3D identity without running the full dev server.
    Action: Add a Canvas-wrapped story for the Infinity component using
    @storybook/nextjs's canvas support. This enables isolated development
    of the 3D identity element.

  [LOW] R-DX-02: No Storybook stories for NavBar, ThemeToggle, or Section.
    These interactive UI components are regression-prone but untested in
    Storybook. ThemeToggle especially benefits from isolated story-driven
    development since it drives global state.
    Action: Add stories for NavBar (with/without active section), ThemeToggle
    (each mode), and Section (with and without visual slot).

  [LOW] R-DX-03: useInfinityMotion hook is undiscoverable — not exported from
    the top-level three/index.ts barrel.
    Even if the hook is kept (per R-ARCH-02 Option B), it is invisible to
    consumers of the feature module. If a developer wants to add rotation to
    a new 3D object, they would not find it via IDE autocomplete.
    Action: Re-export from features/three/index.ts once it has a consumer.
    Until then, treat as internal.

